                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d751">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.9331/264: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-13T22:00:00+07:00"
                            >February 13, 1944—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 13—1:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>290. Suggestion that we should negotiate separate consular convention (see
                    paragraph 3 your 192, February 8, 10 p.m.) is based on my understanding that it
                    is regarded by our Government as preferable to segregate consular provisions in
                    a separate convention so that, in event of any contingency requiring abrogation
                    of treaty of commerce, consular rights and privileges will not be affected by
                    such action.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
